{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513771"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:13:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:13:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12214"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12214"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.66,0.25,0.02,0.07,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4741"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107181"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4741"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12214"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89636"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"297"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"4100"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"},{"type":"tags","id":"12915"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"12929"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7471"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8514"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16052"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36026"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43303"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107181"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic after a self-collected cervical screening test returned positive for Human Papillomavirus (HPV) 16/18. She denies vaginal bleeding, dyspareunia or changes in discharge. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. Her menstrual cycle is usually 30 days long with seven days of bleeding. She has a contraceptive implant and has had five sexual partners in the last year. She was vaccinated against HPV at age 16. She is a non-smoker and drinks two glasses of wine per day. On examination, she appears well with a BMI of 28 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Physical examination is otherwise unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Refer for colposcopy","Perform an urgent cervical co-test","Refer urgently for a LLETZ procedure","Repeat co-test in six weeks","Repeat cervical screening test in five years"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the positive result for HPV 16/18 (a genotype strongly associated with cervical cancer), \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral for colposcopy\u003C/strong\u003E is required to investigate for cervical cancer. Whilst cervical cancer can present in other ways, such as postcoital bleeding, most cases are diagnosed on the basis of an abnormal cervical screening test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs this was a self-collected sample, it is only tested for the presence of HPV and reflex liquid based cytology is not possible. On physician-collected samples, any positive HPV result will have reflex LBC testing to assess for abnormal cervical cells. Guidelines currently recommend that if reflex LBC cannot be performed (due to self-collected sample or inadequate cells on clinician collected sample) then this should be taken at the time of colposcopy for patients with HPV 16/18, or the patient should be recalled to their general practitioner for a clinician collected CST for patients with HPV (not 16/18).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervical co-test\u003C/strong\u003E alone would not change the management as any patient with HPV 16/18 will require a colposcopy, regardless of the LBC result. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ELLETZ procedure\u003C/strong\u003E, or large loop excision of the transformation zone, is indicated for cases of cervical intraepithelial neoplasia. This procedure can be done under local anaesthetic so is convenient, however colposcopy is required first to determine if a LLETZ is the appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeating the co-test in 6 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is not correct as the concerning nature of the initial co-test findings requires further investigation and it is already known that HPV is present. It is not recommended to perform a co-test for LBC if unable to be done on the initial sample as this can be collected at the time of colposcopy which is required for high risk HPV (16/18) regardless of LBC results. Repeating the co-test in 6 weeks is only indicated for unsatisfactory samples (e.g. collection was done incorrectly).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeating the standard cervical screening test in 5 years\u003C/strong\u003E would only be correct if her initial test was negative for HPV.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["If HPV 16/18 is detected on a cervical screening test, referral for colposcopy is required."],"references":["Cervical cancer screening. In: Cancer Council Australia [online]. 2022 [cited 2023 Mar 7]. Available at: https://www.cancer.org.au/clinical-guidelines/cervical-cancer-screening","Australian Cancer Council cervical screening program flowchart. In: Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care [online]. 2020 [cited 2023 Mar 7]. Available at: https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/cervical-screening-pathway-update-v3.jpg","FAQs for providers. In: Cancer Council Australia [online]. 2022 [cited 2023 April 23]. Available at: https://www.cancer.org.au/assets/pdf/national-cervical-screening-program-clinical-guidelines-faqs-for-providers","Rayner M, Welp A, Stoler MH, Cantrell LA. Cervical Cancer Screening Recommendations: Now and for the Future. Healthcare (Basel). 2023 Aug 11;11(16):2273. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10454304/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89636"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12214"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89636"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-25T21:41:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T21:42:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4741"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107181"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"